{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506516"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:43:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:43:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2544"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2544"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.27,0.04,0.07,0.56]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2544"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49363"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2544"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2544"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34614"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2486"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13641"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35476"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42521"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43182"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49363"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old male presents to his general practitioner with palpitations. His medical history include hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia, type II diabetes and stage 5 chronic kidney disease (CKD) as a result of diabetic nephropathy. Medications include perindopril, atorvastatin and insulin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse is irregularly irregular. Heart sounds are dual with no added sounds or murmurs. An ECG confirms atrial fibrillation and he is started on metoprolol for rate control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine clearance is calculated to be 13 mL/min.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aspirin","Apixaban","Clopidogrel","Dabigatran","Warfarin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient should be considered for anticoagulation for stroke prevention in the setting of atrial fibrillation. The decision of which anticoagulant to use is impacted by his severe renal failure. Providing that this patient is able to comply with the regular monitoring required, \u003Cstrong\u003Ewarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E would be the medication of choice. A particular advantage of warfarin is that it is fully reversible. It is also non-dialysable (will not be flushed out in dialysis i.e. will maintain a therapeutic effect), which is important as dialysis will likely be a consideration for this patient in the future. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn a patient with better kidney function, a direct-acting oral anticoagulant (DOAC) would be used. \u003Cstrong\u003EDabigatran\u003C/strong\u003E may be used if creatinine clearance is \u0026gt; 30 mL/min, Rivaroxaban if creatinine clearance is \u0026gt; 15ml/min, and \u003Cstrong\u003EApixaban\u003C/strong\u003E if creatinine clearance is \u0026gt; 25 mL/min.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntiplatelets such as \u003Cstrong\u003Easpirin\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eclopidogrel\u003C/strong\u003E are not suitable for the prevention of ischaemic stroke in AF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf urgent anticoagulation was required, then a heparin bridge could be considered, but a one-to-two day delay waiting for warfarin to become effective is unlikely to be of great concern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnfortunately, this patient is at an increased risk of major bleeding given his comorbidities and age. This should be factored when weighing up the decision to commence anticoagulation, and the patient counselled on his risks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Warfarin is the long-term anticoagulant of choice in patients with poor renal function"],"references":["Atrial fibrillation [Internet]. eTG Complete. 2017. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etgcompleteAtrial fibrillation","Brieger D, Amerena J, Attia J, et al. National Heart Foundation of Australia and the Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Australian Clinical Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Atrial Fibrillation 2018. Heart, Lung Circ. 2018; 27:1209-66."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34614"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2544"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34614"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-28T17:29:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-06T08:41:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2544"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49363"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"re